                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">[</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Well, the reward (high DPS, ability to kill "boss" type mobs, the soloability) was deemed too high and Sony adjusted it. Was it a bit harsh? Possibly. Could they figure out something better? Absolutely. Should you guys get some compensation? I think so, but not in damage. Do I think Charm should have been left alone? Absolutely not.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Now, personally, I don't think it's *that* unbalancing that enchanters do more DPS than other classes in 3 or 4 zones in the whole game; I don't think it was that unbalancing that in Kael, a single zone in Velious, you could use charm mobs to tank on raids. I feel that there's SO MUCH content in EQ that these limited instances where enchanters wield a high degree of power are more than outweighed by the 87 other zones where charm is inferior, unusable, or too difficult.
<br />

<br />
Similarly, I don't begrudge Mages zones like BoT, where their superior charm spell can really shine; I don't begrudge necros undead mobs, where *sigh* yet <span style="font-style: italic">another</span> class is a superior slower than me.
<br />

<br />
Class balance will always be a little 'fuzzy'. There are some mobs on which paladins and shadowknights are simply better tanking choices than warriors. This sort of thing helps add some variety and fun to the game.
<br />

<br />
However, it's evidently a sensitive issue for Mages (and other DPS classes) to be outdamaged a select number of zones. And since out of camp crowd control is better than mezzing in every zone in the game past Luclin currently, I'd *much* rather see charm reimplemented in a manner that helps us in that area than sit here and quibble about DPS. I could really care less about my DPS.[/i]</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
